b only","Antibody only","Antibody and complement C3b","Complement C3a only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibody and complement C3b\u003C/strong\u003E provides the most effective opsonisation because antibodies bind to specific antigens on the microorganism and to Fc receptors on phagocytes, whilst complement C3b binds to complement receptors on phagocytes. When used together, they create multiple binding sites that enhance recognition and attachment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody and complement C3a\u003C/strong\u003E would be less effective since C3a is not an opsonin but rather an anaphylatoxin that promotes inflammation and attracts immune cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3b only\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibody only\u003C/strong\u003E provide fewer binding sites and therefore less effective opsonisation compared to the combination. \u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3a only\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide opsonisation at all, as C3a functions as an inflammatory mediator rather than an opsonin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Opsonisation is most effective when both antibodies and complement C3b are present due to their synergistic effect.","Complement C3b and antibodies bind to different receptors on phagocytes, enhancing recognition and binding.","C3a is an anaphylatoxin that promotes inflammation but does not function as an opsonin."],"references":["Tigner A, Ibrahim SA, Murray IV. Histology, White Blood Cell. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563148/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Thau L, Asuka E, Mahajan K. Physiology, Opsonization. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Pu